      "East Haddam's terrain is among the most challenging for paving work in all of southeastern Connecticut. The town's topography is defined by the Connecticut River valley on its western edge and a series of steep, rocky ridges and narrow stream valleys extending eastward. Driveways in East Haddam frequently climb or descend significant grades — some approaching fifteen percent slopes — and these steep pitches create engineering demands that flat-terrain contractors are simply not equipped to handle. Water moving downhill on a steep driveway accelerates rapidly, and without proper management it will erode edges, scour the asphalt surface, and deposit debris at the bottom of the grade. We design East Haddam's steep driveways with engineered grade breaks that reduce the effective slope between drainage features, cross-slope water bars or paved swales that divert runoff to the sides at regular intervals, and reinforced edge treatments that resist erosion from concentrated flow. At the base of steep driveways, catch basins or stone-lined aprons dissipate runoff energy before it reaches the public road.",
